from nltk.corpus import gutenberg
from urllib import request  
url = "https://www.gutenberg.org/files/161/161-0.txt" 
response = request.urlopen(url) 
sense_text = response.read().decode('utf8')
In [57]:
# Question 1. NER tags for nltk
sense_tok = nltk.word_tokenize(sense_text)
sense_pos = nltk.pos_tag(sense_tok)
sense_chunks = nltk.ne_chunk(sense_pos)
iob_tagged = tree2conlltags(sense_chunks)
pprint(iob_tagged[1:50])

    if hasattr(chunk, 'label'):
        if chunk.label() == "PERSON":  
            print(chunk.label(), ' '.join(c[0] for c in chunk))

# Question 3. i found longest sentences by number of tokens
# output shows longest sentence then visuals under it then the next sentence under it 
# with visuals as well
sentences = [sent for sent in sense_doc.sents]
sentence_lengths = [(len([token for token in sent]), sent) for sent in sentences]
sentence_lengths.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)

longest_sentences = [sent for (length, sent) in sentence_lengths[:2]]

print("The two longest sentences are:")
for sent in longest_sentences:
    print("-", sent)
    displacy.render(nlp(sent.text), style="dep", jupyter=True)

long even affect to demur; especially as Mrs. Jennings’s entreaty was
warmly seconded by Mr. Palmer, who seemed to feel a relief to himself,
in leaving behind him a person so well able to assist or advise Miss
Dashwood in any emergence.

# Question 4. These are all the tokens that have different NER tags 
# for spacy and nltk
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize
from nltk import pos_tag
nltk_tokens = word_tokenize(sense_text)
tagged = pos_tag(nltk_tokens)
spacy_ners = [ent.label_ for ent in sense_doc.ents]


for i, (word, nltk_ner) in enumerate(tagged):
    spacy_ner = spacy_ners[i] if i < len(spacy_ners) else None
    if nltk_ner != spacy_ner:
        print(f"{word}: nltk NER = {nltk_ner}, spacy NER = {spacy_ner}")

NER is a very useful tool that is used to extract important information from the text using classification and analysis. There are differences between the NER tags used in SpaCy and NLTK: I noticed that SpaCy has more types of NER tags, which could be useful for more precise tagging. NLTK NER tags, however, seem to be more customizable and flexible. I think that this makes SpaCy tags more efficient and accurate, but NLTK NER tags could be easier when it comes to getting more particular tagging and using larger datasets.

# Question 5.
sentence = "The assistant managing editor made the final edits on the novel."

tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(sentence)
tagged = nltk.pos_tag(tokens)

pattern = r"""
    NP: {<DT>?<JJ>*<NN|NNS>(<VBG><NN|NNS>)+}
"""
cp = nltk.RegexpParser(pattern)

result = cp.parse(tagged)
print(result)

(S
  (NP The/DT assistant/NN managing/VBG editor/NN)
  made/VBD
  the/DT
  final/JJ
  edits/NNS
  on/IN
  the/DT
  novel/NN
  ./.)

# Question 6.
sentence = "July and August are my favorite months."

tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(sentence)
tagged = nltk.pos_tag(tokens)

pattern = r"""
    NP: {<NNP><CC><NNP>|<DT><PRP\$><NNS><CC><NNS>|<NN><NNS><CC><NNS>}
"""
cp = nltk.RegexpParser(pattern)

result = cp.parse(tagged)
print(result)

  (NP July/NNP and/CC August/NNP)
  are/VBP
  my/PRP$
  favorite/JJ
  months/NNS
  ./.)
